Stats SA says South Africa has slipped into a technical recession for the first time since 2009. JOHANNESBURG - There are concerns that with South Africa being in a technical recession, the country is heading towards its worst growth slump in three decades.On Tuesday, Stats SA said adjusted GDP for the first quarter had contracted by 0.7%.In the three months prior to this, GDP contracted by 0.3%.The Reserve Bank has hoped to achieve overall growth of 1% for 2017.Stats SA says South Africa has slipped into a technical recession for the first time since 2009.Nedbank economist Isaac Matshego says the latest figures are concerning. The economy has been on a downturn since December 2013 and it seems like it s going to continue at least for a good part of this year. He says there needs to change soon. It means we re going to be in the longest downturn since the mid-1980s. However, the latest figures show that agriculture expanded in the first quarter by more than 22%, while mining saw growth of almost 13%.Meanwhile, Treasury says it's concerned that the current economic growth if sustained, will lead to a further decline in GDP per capita and revenue - risking the sustainability of the country's fiscal framework.(Edited by Winnie Theletsane)